\par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\widctlpar \b\f4\fs40\cf2 Capua
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
\par Career level: Engineer (salary 5 Dn)
\par Starting City Funds: 8000 Dn
\par Highest Housing Level: Grand Villa
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Overview
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
This is the 1st peaceful mission. After the two training levels, the shackles are removed and you are given plenty of freedom to build what you want, right from the start. This level is quite forgiving, so go ahead and experiment, you can even afford to m
ake a few mistakes. Don't run out of money, and everything will work out in the end.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Targets
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 2500\tab population
\par 35\tab Culture
\par 10\tab Prosperity
\par 20\tab Peace
\par 60\tab Favor
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Trade Partners
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
\par Syracusae (sea route) \tab sells 15 meat [per year]
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 sells 15 marble
\par buys 15 olives
\par buys 25 oil
\par buys 15 furniture
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 
\par Tarentum (land route) \tab sells 15 furniture
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 sells 15 wine
\par buys 25 pottery
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Important Events
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Jan 350 BC\tab The level begins
\par Jul 348 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 oil
\par Apr 345 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 oil
\par Note: there are no barbarian invasions
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Disasters
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 None
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Hints & Tips
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
Keep in mind the population requirement, keep an eye on unemployment and city funds, and learn to take a look at the Fire and Damage risks overlays from time to time. Apart from that, experiment, experiment, experiment. Don't be afraid to make a few mista
kes. The training levels were for learning the basics, and now this level and the next one are for mastering them.
\par 
\par A checklist of lessons:
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 1.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Producing manufactured goods (pottery, furniture, oil)
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 2.\tab}Exporting manufactured goods
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 3.\tab}Importing (marble)
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 4.\tab}Keeping an eye on city funds
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 5.\tab}Using the Fire risk overlay
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 6.\tab}Using the Damage risk overlay
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 7.\tab}Using the Water overlay
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 8.\tab}How to evolve your houses (start by right-clicking on them)
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 9.\tab}Managing unemployment
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 \page 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\keepn\widctlpar \b\f4\fs40\cf2 Tarraco
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
\par Career level: Architect (salary 8 Dn)
\par Starting City Funds: 8000 Dn
\par Highest Housing Level: Medium Insulae
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Overview
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 This is the 2nd peaceful mission. Build upon your strategies from Capua, expect the unexpected, and kiss up to Caesar every chance you get.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Targets
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 2500\tab population
\par 45\tab Culture
\par 25\tab Prosperity
\par 30\tab Peace
\par 70\tab Favor
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Trade Partners
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Capua (sea route)\tab \tab sells 25 timber [per year]
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 buys 40 wheat
\par buys 25 fruit
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 
\par Tarentum (sea route)\tab sells 15 furniture
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 buys 25 marble
\par buys 15 pottery
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Important Events
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Jan 270 BC\tab The level begins
\par Apr 269 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 pottery
\par Sep 267 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 fruit
\par Mar 265 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 pottery
\par Aug 265 BC\tab Fruit price increased by 20 Dn
\par May 263 BC\tab Emperor requests 25 fruit
\par Jul 262 BC\tab Marble price increased by 20 Dn
\par Sep 261 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 pottery
\par Mar 259 BC\tab Emperor requests 20 fruit
\par May 257 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 pottery
\par May 255 BC\tab Furniture price increased by 20 Dn
\par Jun 255 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 fruit
\par Mar 250 BC\tab Fruit price decreased by 15 Dn
\par Sep 250 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 fruit
\par Sep 245 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 fruit
\par Note1: there are no more Emperor requests after 245BC
\par Note2: there are no barbarian invasions
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Disasters
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 An earthquake hits in June 268 BC, destroying a large part of the main farmland. It will split the farmland into three sections. You 
can still build a bridge to the (now) smaller farmland sections to keep using them, although you cannot bridge the canyons left behind by the earthquake.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Hints & Tips
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 If you're not sure whether you've mastered the basics on Capua, then experiment some more on this level.
\par Apart from the earthquake, the only problem you might have is the high favor rating requirement. There aren't many opportunities to build up the favor rating, but you don't need to give any gifts to Caesar to pass the level, if you don't ha
ng around for TOO long.
\par 
\par To put food items (eg. Fruit) into a warehouse, tell the trade advisor to stockpile that item. You can only send fruit to the emperor if it's in a warehouse, not granary.
\par 
\par If you have any real problems with the favor rating, send gifts to Caesar, with 12 months between gifts.
\par \page 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\keepn\widctlpar \b\f4\fs40\cf2 Miletus
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
\par Career level: Quaestor (salary 12 Dn)
\par Starting City Funds: 7000 Dn
\par Highest housing level: Grand Villa
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Overview
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 This is the 3rd peaceful mission. Finally, city defenses will factor into the equation. Being the first desert level, it also brings a new set of problems into your city building strategies.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Targets
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 5000\tab population
\par 60\tab Culture
\par 35\tab Prosperity
\par 40\tab Peace
\par 40\tab Favor
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Trade Partners
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Corinthus (sea route)\tab sells 15 clay [per year]
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 sells 15 pottery
\par buys 15 weapons
\par buys 25 fruit
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 
\par Athanae (sea route)\tab sells 25 wheat
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 sells 15 wine
\par sells 15 marble
\par buys 15 fish
\par buys 15 oil
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Important Events
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Jan 220 BC\tab The level begins
\par Oct 217 BC\tab Greek invasion from the southwest
\par Oct 217 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 weapons
\par Mar 215 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 furniture
\par May 215 BC\tab Oil price increased by 20 Dn
\par Sep 214 BC\tab Greek invasion from the northwest
\par Jul 213 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 weapons
\par May 211 BC\tab Greek invasion from the southwest
\par Jul 210 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 furniture
\par Jul 210 BC\tab Weapons price increased by 10 Dn
\par Sep 210 BC\tab Corinthus now buys 25 weapons per year
\par Jun 208 BC\tab Greek invasion from the northwest
\par Jul 207 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 weapons
\par Jul 205 BC\tab Corinthus now sells 25 clay per year
\par Oct 204 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 furniture
\par Aug 203 BC\tab Greek invasion from the southwest
\par May 200 BC\tab Wine price increased by 35 Dn
\par Jun 200 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 weapons
\par Jul 200 BC\tab Marble price increased by 40 Dn
\par Aug 198 BC\tab Greek invasion from the northwest
\par Oct 195 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 weapons
\par Apr 193 BC\tab Greek invasion from the northwest
\par Oct 190 BC\tab Emperor requests 15 furniture
\par Oct 188 BC\tab Greek invasion from the southwest
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Disasters
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Occasionally your city's water supply will be contaminated, reducing the city's overall health level
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Hints & Tips
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 This level introduces you to some of the more advanced problems in the game, and provides new challenges for you as a governor.
\par 
\par Here are some tips on how to deal with the new challenges:
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 1.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Fires - desert cities have a greatly increased fire risk, so you should build more prefects than usual, and spend even more time checking the fire risk overlay.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 2.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Water - fountains in the desert only service a range of 3 tiles, instead of 4 (for central and northern cities). Therefore, if you've fashioned your earlier cities using 9x9 city blocks, you should change to 7x7 blocks, for the desert.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 3.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Population - this level calls for double the population of the previous levels. As a result you will need to build more of everything, and that makes it more difficult to keep an eye on every little detail. Therefore, make sure you build all parts of your
 city such that they can look after themselves for extended periods of time. If they can't look after themselves, you will be permanently fighting fire all over the city!
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 4.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Invasions - Greek soldiers will invade you from two points of the map. If you preempt the invasion points and surround them with walls and towers, you will never need to build any forts. However, you are free to make city defense more "interesting" by bui
lding walls and towers around the city if you wish, plus a few forts. The invading force is always the same approximate size (between half dozen to a dozen troops).
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 5.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Choices - Miletus has plenty of open spaces, and the choice between coastline (fishing) or farmland (fruit) as your population center, is not a very straightforward one. I'd recommend building around the larger farmland, because your farms, docks and hous
es must all be together, for the purposes of exporting oil and importing clay. The farmland can support 18 farms, and you should use 2 or 3 of those for olive farms.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 6.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Fishing - bui
ld a ship bridge from the coast (near the farms) to the first large island. Use this island to build more wharves. That should give you enough fish (along with the 15 fruit farms) to feed all of your people.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 7.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Exports - you have enough problems producing food for your people without trying to export it as well, so just stick to exporting oil and weapons. 
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 8.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Imports - the only thing you'll want to import is clay. Don't import the others unless you have too much money. 

\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 9.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Prosperity - although the pr
osperity target is not overly high, you still won't meet it just by accident while concentrating on building tents! Right click on the houses and give them the goods and services to allow them to evolve to a level between small insulae and grand insulae.

\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 \page 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\keepn\widctlpar \b\f4\fs40\cf2 Lugdunum
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
\par Career level: Procurator (salary 20 Dn)
\par Starting City Funds: 5000 Dn
\par Highest housing level: Grand Villa
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Overview
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 This is the 4th peaceful mission, and your job is to learn how to fit lots of people into a small amount of high-level housing, whic
h is one of the key ingredients to prosperity. The other key ingredient is that of managing your money. Although you've been doing a lot of trading on previous levels, you will be introduced to a lot of stops and starts on your trade routes here, which wi
ll pressure your financial control.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Targets
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 5000\tab population
\par 65\tab Culture
\par 50\tab Prosperity
\par 50\tab Peace
\par 45\tab Favor
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Trade Partners
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Mediolanum (land route)\tab sells 15 fruit [per year]
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 sells 25 timber
\par buys 15 weapons
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 
\par Massilia (land route)\tab sells 15 vines
\par }\pard \s18\fi720\li1440\widctlpar {\f4 sells 25 oil
\par buys 15 marble
\par buys 25 pottery
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Important Events
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 Jan 170 BC\tab The level begins
\par Jan 168 BC\tab New trade route available to Massilia
\par Mar 167 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 meat
\par Oct 165 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 meat
\par Apr 162 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 meat
\par Jul 159 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 marble
\par Sep 157 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 marble
\par Jul 155 BC\tab Pottery price reduced by 20 dn
\par Apr 154 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 marble
\par Apr 150 BC\tab Emperor requests 10 meat
\par Note: there are no barbarian invasions
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Disasters
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 
Occasional landslides will stop land traders from reaching your city for a few months. Be prepared for these cuts in your main source of income, by keeping city funds at 1000 to 2000 Dn. Don't spend every cent as soon as you earn it. Otherwise you'll go i
nto debt, Caesar will be mad, and you'll be forced to deal with a lot more troubles than is strictly necessary.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar \f5\ul\cf12 Hints & Tips
\par \pard\plain \s18\widctlpar \f11\fs20 {\f4 The main problem that most players have with Lugdunum, is food distribution and lack of workers. Here are a few ideas to overcome these problems:
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 1.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Pause the game at the beginning and build aqeducts around the 2 packs of wolves (they work just as well as walls, for wolf control, and cost less). Build a javelin unit later on, and move them near the wolves. They can shoot over the aqueducts to kill the
 wolves, and can do it quickly enough to stop any wolves from being reborn. Once the javelin unit has been built, demolish the barracks to reclaim some workers.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 2.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Build low bridges to connect the islands. There are no ships on this lev
el so don't waste money building ship bridges.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 3.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Demolish the natives' roads and rebuild them in such a way that you can cover all of the native's houses with only 2 or 3 missionary posts
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 4.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Don't build prefectures, hospitals or the hippodrome. You don't need them on this level. Keep your people happy by managing unemployment and throwing a festival once in a while so that you have no problems with riots.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 5.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Try to fit 99% of your population in the natives' area, between the two farmlands. If you can't manage this, the next best thing is to build on the large farming hill. Try not to build anything but houses and the bare necessity services in this population
 center. This way, you'll have less trouble letting people live near the food supplies, and also it may encourage you to keep away from building more services than you need, and that will help alleviate pressure on workforce shortages.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 6.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Don't build acad
emies or colosseums in the population center. Build them elsewhere if you think you need them for the culture rating or "overall" entertainment level.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 7.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Build a few tents, but not too many, to support your workers for the export industries which you'll want to build somewhere away from your main population center.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 8.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Build only enough (small) temples to provide religion "coverage" for the populace. Have at least 1 to each god, and the same number for each, except maybe build one extra to Neptune or Ven
us (not both), to keep him/her permanently exalted. After the small temples, build only oracles, and build them away from your population centers.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 9.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 Don't import fruit.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 10.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Don't import vines to make wine. You can achieve the prosperity rating without building any villas. If you do build villas that will only make matters worse because of the workforce shortage problem. You can, and will want to, achieve the prosperity by ha
ving almost all of your houses at insulae level. By not importing vines, you al
so reduce pressure on your purse string, via lesser imports and increased trader turnaround time, ie. traders can get out of the city quicker, allowing the next group of traders to arrive sooner. You also save on warehouse and workshop workers by not maki
ng wine.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 11.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Build only one pig farm. Use it , a nearby warehouse set to accept only meat, and tell your trade advisor to stockpile meat. Use this only to satisfy Caesar's requests. All the rest should be wheat farms. Feed your people nothing but wheat.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 12.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Try not to make the same mistake I did, of building the export industry too far away from the domestic industry. You'll have fewer hassles with the traders if you build them closer.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 13.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Don't get your population too high too early. Take some time to get the food production & storage well and truly rolling along, before you build any markets. 5 to 10 full granaries would be my suggested minimum before building any markets. If you like, yo
u can segregate your housing into sectors using gatehouses. This
 way, you can build markets for one sector before the others, and gradually phase in the initial food grab. After the initial grab for food, empty out and then demolish any granaries that are just taking up space. 4 half-full granaries are not as good as 
2 full ones. You also save on workers.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 14.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Build more markets than you usually would, but don't go mad with them. One market for every 500 people should be sufficient. More markets equals more stable housing, but the people won't consume more just because
 there are more markets! You especially don't want your houses to constantly evolve/devolve on this level because it takes so long for new immigrants to get to the houses and replace those you lost during the devolution.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 15.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Right click on your granaries and warehouses, and use the special orders screen to set some of them to "get" certain types of food & goods. The granaries furthest from farms (and coincidentally, should be nearest to houses) should get the food from other 
granaries. This saves your market ladies some legwork, so that they can spend more time making subsequent trips to either get more food, or to get other types of goods.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 16.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
Don't build barbers until you're nearly finished. In the meantime, fill up one warehouse full of oil, and stop. Leave the advisor on "importing" oil, but don't let any other warehouses accept it. This will help you spend less on imports, while improving t
urn-around time for the traders from Massilia, who buy marble and pottery. When the end is within sight, build t
he barbers, and watch as your medium insulaes evolve to large insulae (fingers crossed), to give you that final push for prosperity, if you needed it.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\pndec }{\f4 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\fs20 17.\tab}}\pard \s18\fi-360\li360\widctlpar\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnhang{\pntxta .}}{\f4 
When your prosperity rating is taken care of, use areas away from the population center, for building the schools, libraries, theaters and academies you need to achieve the culture rating.
\par }\pard \s18\widctlpar {\f4 \page 
